blocks.value: Feasibility trial of an unsupervised, facility-based exercise programme for depressed outpatients

This pilot study examined feasibility of an unsupervised, facilitybased exercise programme for promoting exercise adherence among depressed adult outpatients. The potential effect of adding physical activity counselling on depressive symptoms and physical activity was also explored. Participants were randomly assigned to a 12-week programme comprising an orientation and access to fitness centre resources (control, n = 18)  or that programme plus 6 physical activity counselling sessions (intervention, n = 18). Outcome measures were feasibility (fitness centre attendance over 12 weeks); Beck Depression Inventory (BDI-II) and International Physical Activity Questionnaire (IPAQ) completed at baseline and week 12; and qualitative programme feedback. Fitness centre attendance averaged only 12 days (14% of all possible days) with no differences between study groups. No group differences were found on IPAQ or BDI-II scores at week 12. Increases from baseline in IPAQ moderate/vigorous activity minutes were associated with decreases in BDI-II scores at week 12 (p < 0.001). The most helpful programme aspect reported was connecting participants to fitness centre resources. In this pilot study of depressed outpatients, an unsupervised fitness centre based program was not feasible for promoting exercise adherence and adding physical activity counselling was not useful for increasing physical activity levels or reducing depression.

Depressed adults are less physically active and have lower fitness levels than the general population. Exercise is an evidence-based treatment for depression with exercise effects comparable to cognitive behavioural therapy or antidepressant medication. Proposed mechanisms accounting for exercise response among depressed individuals include neurobiological adaptations and increases in self-efficacy. Emerging evidence indicates that exercise interventions may have added mood benefits among patients receiving concurrent antidepressant therapy or medication non-responders.
A 2016 meta-analysis evaluated exercise as a treatment for depression among mostly outpatient populations. A total of 25 trials (involving 1487 participants) were included; 9 trials included patients with major depressive disorder (MDD) while 14 included patients with elevated depressive symptoms. The majority (72%, 18/25) of studies used supervised, facility-based exercise, 3 included unsupervised (home-based) programmes, and 2 utilized both formats. Overall, both supervised and unsupervised formats were effective for reducing depression. However, among patients with MDD, larger effects were found for interventions supervised by exercise professionals. In the United Kingdom, supervised exercise programmes, thrice weekly, over 10-14 weeks, are recommended as a treatment option for people with depression (National Institute for Health and Care Excellence, 2016). However, supervised programmes reduce intervention scalability. From the literature, it is also not clear how much support, supervision, and structure is needed among patients with MDD for enhancing adherence to exercise and depressive symptom reduction. Only one study compared home-based and supervised facility-based exercise programmes with no differences found on depressive symptom reduction. Therefore, additional research on different delivery formats for exercise programmes among patients with MDD is warranted.
This pilot study evaluated the feasibility for promoting exercise adherence of an unsupervised, facility-based, exercise programme consisting of an orientation and access to fitness centre resources among outpatients with MDD. In addition, we explored the potential effect of adding physical activity counselling to the exercise programme on physical activity levels and depressive symptoms, using a pilot, two-group, randomized, controlled study design.

Eligible patients were sent a medical information form to complete and return. After receiving the patient's release of medical information, an investigator sent a letter to the patient's identified physician requesting his/her physician's opinion of the patient's ability to participate in exercise. Physicians also received copies of the patient's release of information, a copy of the health screen for exercise, and a pre-addressed return envelope. After receiving clearance from the physician, the potential participant was scheduled fora baseline session. At this visit, participants read and signed the consent form and completed a number of self-report measures.
After completing the baseline assessment, participants were randomly assigned with 1:1 allocation to one of two 12-week, individual-based interventions described below. Prior to the trial, the study statistician generated the random allocation sequence. Participants completed the baseline assessment prior to being informed of their allocation to study conditions. Clinic-based assessments were conducted at baseline and the end-of-treatment (week 12). The research assistant conducting the assessments was blind to treatment condition. As part of a sub-study, one year after study enrolment, research staff attempted to contact all participants by telephone to obtain qualitative programme feedback.

Exercise programme common to both study groups All participants received a free membership, orientation, and access to the worksite fitness centre fora 12 week period. Participants received the standard of care provided to all fitness centre members that included a fitness assessment and individuallytailored exercise prescription.
The fitness assessment comprised: a 6-12 minute submaximal cardiorespiratory test on a cycle ergometer based on the Astrand Ryhming Protocol; evaluation of trunk flexibility measured with a standard sit-and-reach box, utilizing the ACSM (American College of Sports Medicine [ACSM], 2014) protocol; resting heart rate taken fora 30 second period via the radial pulse and multiplied by two to provide the minute value; blood pressure taken manually using a Tyocs sphygmomanometer; and body composition measured by bioelectrical impedance (Tanita Body Fat Analyzer, TBF 305). If a participant had a pacemaker or implantable cardioverter/defibrillator, body composition was assessed using via skin callipers, as opposed to bioelectrical impedance.
The individually-tailored exercise prescription included aerobic exercise, strength training, stretching, and recommendations to exercise regularly. The exercise prescription was based on the cardio-respiratory fitness test and the ACSM (ACSM, 2014) guidelines recommending 30 minutes or more of moderate-vigorous intensity exercise on at least 5 days per week. Participants were invited to ask questions of the fitness centre staff at anytime. Exercise at the fitness centre and at home were both encouraged but no supervised exercise was provided. Participants were provided with an access card which was scanned upon entrance to the fitness centre to document attendance.

Participants receiving this condition additionally received six 30-minute individuallytailored sessions with an exercise counsellor. Sessions were held at the fitness centre in a conference room or office at weeks 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, and 11. Participants also had email access to the counsellor once per week. The intervention was based on social-cognitive theory. The counsellor utilized several motivational strategies such as behavioural contracts for exercise goals, lists of personal barriers to exercise and potential solutions, goal-setting, and problem-solving. The sessions also emphasized the benefits of exercise for depressed patients. Table describes the topics, content, and homework for each session.
Participants were provided with written educational materials on exercise and were encouraged to reread and think about the session topic at home prior to the next scheduled session. The counsellor assisted participants to identify personally relevant aspects of the materials. Participants were encouraged to ask questions in all sessions. Participants were also asked to email their counsellor onetime per week to check in regarding exercise. The counsellor responded with reinforcement and adherence encouragement. The counsellor contacted participants if they missed a session and rescheduled the session that same week or conducted a make-up telephone session.
The exercise counsellor had a background in health education and substantial experience delivering exercise interventions as part of a research protocol. The counsellor received training on the intervention protocol and monitored delivery of intervention components using a checklist. Sessions were audiotaped and a random sample of 10% of early, middle, and late sessions was evaluated based on a checklist. The counsellor checklists and audiotapes revealed over 90% adherence to the protocol, indicating that the treatment was delivered with high fidelity.

Self-report items assessed age, gender, race/ethnicity, marital status, education level, current tobacco use, current use of psychotherapy and pharmacotherapy at baseline. Body weight was assessed using a calibrated scale.

Attendance at the fitness centre was documented via on-site card access scanners. Data were obtained from the fitness centre at the end of the 12 week program and summarized as the average total number of days attended of 84 possible days (i.e. 12 weeks). As another indication of feasibility, study retention was summarized as the percentage of enrolled participants who completed week 12 assessment. Moreover, among intervention participants only, session adherence was recorded by the counsellor and summarized as the proportion of 6 sessions attended. Benefits of exercise (general and depression-specific). Empirical evidence for the benefits of exercise was discussed in lay person's terms.
Complete a list of personally-relevant benefits of exercise.
Session 2 (week 3) How to use exercise to manage mood. Short bouts of exercise as coping strategy and regular physical activity for overall decrease in depressive symptoms.
Create individualized list of occasions when short bout maybe helpful. Complete behavioral contract for exercise as treatment for depression.
Session 3 (week 5) Goal-setting. The exercise counselor presented exercise goal-setting information, emphasizing SMART (specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, task-oriented) goals.
Generate and record personal goals.
Session 4 (week 7) Barriers to exercise and the problem of non-adherence. Non-adherence and barriers to exercise require individualized problem-solving and strategies to enhance motivation and reinforcement.
Practice problem-solving around barriers. Create list of potentially useful strategies to address barriers and nonadherence.
Session 5 (week 9) Evaluation of exercise goals and accomplishments. Personal successes and challenges with adhering to exercise program were discussed. The need to continually evaluate exercise behavior was emphasized. Modification of goals and continued problem-solving was encouraged.
Create list of the positive change with respect to exercise (e.g. gained knowledge, increased activity level, met specific goals).
Session 6 (week 11) Long-term adherence to exercise. The physical and psychological benefits were briefly reviewed along with a discussion of the challenge of adherence to exercise long-term. Individually-tailored ways to increase or maintain adherence after study ends was addressed.
Generate personally relevant reasons for continuation of exercise. Generate a list of ways to encourage continued exercise (e.g. reinforcement, variety, continued goal setting).
Stage of change for exercise Stage of change for exercise was assessed at baseline and week 12 using a 4-item validated measure with a yes/no format. Respondents were categorized into one of the five stages of change for exercise: pre-contemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, or maintenance.

The IPAQ is a reliable and valid self-report measure of number of minutes spent in vigorous and moderate physical activities over the past 7 day period that was administered at baseline and at week 12 .

The BDI-II was used to assess depression severity for the previous 7 day period at baseline and at week 12. The BDI-II has established psychometric properties. Scores of 0-13 indicate not depressed, 14-19 are indicative of mild depression, 20-28 indicate moderate depression and 29-63 indicate severe depression.

Eighty-one percent of participants (29/36) were reached by telephone to obtain their feedback on the intervention (15 intervention and 14 control participants). Several themes emerged from the qualitative interviews. The most helpful aspect of study participation reported was connecting participants to the resources available at the fitness centre. Many described being initially intimidated by entering the fitness centre but setting up the appointment for them and arranging fora trained fitness centre staff member to assist them and provide recommendations for exercise was very helpful. For example: 'Before I would have felt strange going into a workout centre alone but having someone meet me and show me where things were made me feel less self-conscious.' Intervention participants additionally valued the support and understanding from an exercise instructor and having someone to be accountable and individualized time with the physical activity counselling. Illustrative quotes were: 'Being face to face with people who understood depression and exercise in depth,' 'The individualized, one on onetime was so important to me.' 'It helped a lotto have someone that I had to be accountable to.'
Overall the least helpful aspects of study participation reported were: 1. the programme did not meet participants' expectations with respect to exercise; 2. completing paperwork/assessments; and 3. difficulty of exercising without supervision/reinforcement. Illustrative quotes related to outcome expectations were: 'I was disappointed that my. . .cardiovascular fitness didn't seem to improve,' 'I didn't get around to working out as much as I should have,' and 'I felt I needed more supervision.'

Means, standard deviations, and select percentiles were summarized for continuous variables and frequency and percentage were used to summarize for categorical variables. All baseline measures were compared between the two study groups using the two-sample t-test (rank sum) for continuous variables and Fisher's exact test for categorical variables. BDI-II scores at baseline were compared for participants who were at baseline in the contemplation stage of change for exercise versus not (i.e. preparation, action or maintenance) using the two-sample rank sum test. Change in IPAQ scores and change in BDI-II scores from baseline were compared at the end of treatment and at the 3 month follow-up assessment using analysis of covariance (ANCOVA). For these analyses, the follow-up score was the dependent variable, and treatment group and baseline score were the independent variables. Spearman's correlation coefficients were used to evaluate the association between change from baseline in IPAQ minutes of moderate/vigorous activity and change in BDI-II depression scores.
When the follow-up information was not present, using an intent-to-treat principle we assumed no change in the measures (last observation carried forward). In all cases, p-values < 0.05 were considered statistically significant.
A qualitative data analysis approach was used to analyse the participant feedback. The interviews were audio taped and transcribed verbatim. Interview transcripts were sorted and coded using N6 qualitative data analysis programme. Participant responses were independently coded by two authors using methods of content analysis, i.e. systematic process of sorting and coding information based on the themes. Independent coding results were compared and important themes and representative quotes were identified. Because the themes were consistent across treatment conditions, the results are presented for the overall sample. study exclusion were lack of clinical diagnosis of MDD or not eligible to use the fitness centre. Of the eligible patients, 5 (10%) declined further participation, 8 (16%) could not be scheduled a baseline assessment, and 36 (74%) were enrolled. Participants were randomly assigned to the control (n = 18) or intervention (n = 18) condition. Table presents the participant characteristics at baseline. Thirty-one women and five men enrolled. The majority (94%) was involved in depression therapy and 97% were taking medication for their depression. The baseline BDI-II score was 22.1 ± 10.8, indicating moderate levels of depression. Physical activity levels, based on the total IPAQ score, were a median of 20 minutes per week, the median number of minutes of walking was 0 (IQR: 0-47.5), and less than 20% of the participants reported any vigorous or moderate exercise. Most participants (83%) were in the contemplation stage of change for exercise. Stage of change for exercise was not significantly associated with BDI-II scores at baseline (p = 0.080). Study groups were comparable with respect to baseline characteristics (all p > 0.05).

Average percentage of days (of 84 total possible days) attending the worksite fitness centre was 12.1 ± 17.4 (10.8 ± 20.8 for control versus 13.5 ± 13.6 days for intervention participants, p = 0.20). Among intervention participants only, 83% completed all six physical counselling sessions. No significant group differences were found with respect to the proportion of participants completing week 12 assessment (83% for PAC intervention vs. 67% for control participants; Fisher's exact p = 0.443) (Figure).

For all participants, stage of change for exercise changed significantly from baseline to week 12 were significant (p = 0.002, signed rank test). Of the 30 subjects reporting the contemplation stage at baseline, 20 had data available at week 12, of which over half (n = 13) were in the action or maintenance stage, 5 remained in contemplation, and 1 reported being in the pre-contemplation stage.

Table displays the IPAQ scores by treatment condition at baseline and week 12. No significant group differences were observed at week 12 on change from baseline in IPAQ scores (total minutes of activity, walking, or moderate/vigorous activity). At week 12, two (11%) of the control participants reported ≥ 150 minutes of moderate/vigorous exercise on the IPAQ compared with seven (39%) in the intervention group; p = 0.12. We additionally explored the association of change in IPAQ minutes of moderate/ vigorous exercise from baseline to week 12 with baseline variables included in Table. After adjusting for treatment group and baseline IPAQ moderate/vigorous activity score, no statistically significant associations were detected.

Table shows the BDI-II scores by treatment condition at baseline and week 12. Depression scores decreased overall but no significant differences were detected between study groups on change from baseline in depression scores at week 12. Association of change in depression and physical activity
We examined for the entire sample whether change in BDI-II score was associated with change from baseline in IPAQ assessed minutes of moderate/vigorous exercise at week 12. A significant (p < 0.001) negative relationship was detected (Spearman's correlation −0.53), indicating reductions in depressive symptoms with increases in moderate/vigorous exercise.

This pilot trial adds to the literature by examining the feasibility for increasing exercise adherence of an unsupervised, facility-based exercise programme among an outpatient clinical sample of adults with. The programme is not feasible based on low attendance at the fitness centre and no significant change from baseline on physical activity levels at the end of treatment. Our results are consistent with another study that found advice and encouragement to increase physical activity was not sufficient for reducing symptoms of depression.
While depressive symptom reductions were observed overall, significant differences were not detected between study groups. One potential explanation is the small sample size limited our ability to detect statistically significant differences between groups. Moreover, most patients were receiving anti-depressant medication therapy which may have masked any potential benefits of physical activity on depression response. Most likely however is that the exercise programme and physical activity counselling may not have been sufficiently intense to impact depressive symptoms or physical activity. At the end of treatment, only about one-third of the intervention participants met the recommended guidelines for exercise of ≥ 150 minutes of moderate/vigorous intensity exercise per week. However, there appeared to be some overall benefit of the programme for positive movement in stage of change for exercise. We observed that overall increases in minutes of moderate/vigorous activity were significantly associated with decreases in depression. These findings, along with other reports suggest efforts are needed to increase exercise to a therapeutic dose among depressed patients.
As with all pilot trials, our findings are limited by the small sample size. Moreover, some characteristics of the sample limit generalizability of the findings. Mostly women, White, educated adults enrolled. Future studies are needed to test exercise programme strategies in diverse populations with MDD. A second limitation is that we used an additive design with active control condition, and future studies would benefit from a delayed treatment control condition or one that equates study groups for contact time. Third, the data obtained from the fitness centre was limited to total number of sessions attended whereas information collected on a weekly basis would have been more informative and linked to the exercise prescription. Fourth, the follow-up occurred a year after study enrolment and some participants may have forgotten some positive or negative aspects of the study. Ideally, the follow-up would have been done more proximal to the programme end.
Despite these limitations, our results point to the need for novel approaches to providing supervised exercise programmes for patients with MDD. Qualitative programme feedback from participants indicated the most helpful aspects of participation were the structured aspects of the exercise programme such as connecting them to the resources available at a worksite fitness centre; and for intervention participants, the support and understanding from an exercise counsellor, someone to be accountable to and individualized time. However, supervised facility-based programmes reduce intervention reach and increase costs. A potential innovation to scale up supervised exercise programmes is using technology such as digital coaching or a robotic telepresence.
